Attaching the event listener to the parent element and using event delegation to listen for clicks on the button is a better option as it allows you to handle events on elements that do not exist yet on the page at the time the JavaScript is executed.

Event delegation works by attaching an event listener to a parent element, and then using the event object to determine which child element was actually clicked on. When an event occurs on an element inside the parent element, it will bubble up the DOM tree and reach the parent element. The event listener on the parent element can then examine the event object to determine which child element was actually clicked on.

To implement event delegation in your code, you can attach the event listener to the parent element (in this case, the element that contains all 5 buttons) instead of each button. Then in the event listener function, you can use the event object's `target` property to determine which button was actually clicked on. For example:
```javascript
const parentElement = document.querySelector('.rating-stars');
parentElement.addEventListener('click', function(event) {
  if (event.target.matches('.rating-stars button')) {
    // do something with the button that was clicked
  }
});
```
This way, you can use the same event listener function for all buttons, regardless of whether they currently exist on the page or not, and you can use the `event.target` property to determine which button was actually clicked on.

Regarding the if statement, you can use event.target.classList.contains("star-fill-100") check if the star is filled or not. Based on this you can decide whether to update the rating with the value or null.

You can re-attach the event listener after updating the class of the button, but that could be less efficient compared to the event delegation approach.

