To achieve this behavior, you can keep track of the currently selected feature and the next number to display on it. When a feature is clicked, you can update the style of the previously selected feature to reset it and set the style and number for the newly selected feature.

Here's an example implementation:
```php
// Define a variable to keep track of the currently selected feature
var selectedFeature = null;

// Define a variable to keep track of the next number to display
var nextNumber = 1;

// Create a new vector layer
var vectorLayer = new ol.layer.Vector({
  source: new ol.source.Vector({
    // Add your polygons to the vector source
    features: [ /* your polygons here */ ]
  }),
  // Add an event listener for the 'click' event
  style: function(feature) {
    var style = new ol.style.Style({
      // Set the default style for the polygons
      fill: new ol.style.Fill({
        color: 'rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.2)'
      }),
      stroke: new ol.style.Stroke({
        color: '#ffcc33',
        width: 2
      })
    });

    // If the feature is selected, change its style and add the number label
    if (feature === selectedFeature) {
      style.setFill(new ol.style.Fill({
        color: 'rgba(255, 0, 0, 0.2)'
      }));
      style.setStroke(new ol.style.Stroke({
        color: '#ff0000',
        width: 2
      }));
      style.setText(new ol.style.Text({
        text: nextNumber.toString(),
        font: 'bold 14px sans-serif',
        fill: new ol.style.Fill({
          color: '#fff'
        })
      }));
    }

    return style;
  }
});

// Add the vector layer to the map
map.addLayer(vectorLayer);

// Add an event listener for the 'click' event on the vector layer
vectorLayer.on('click', function(event) {
  // Get the clicked feature
  var feature = event.feature;

  // If a feature was previously selected, reset its style
  if (selectedFeature) {
    selectedFeature.setStyle(null);
  }

  // Set the style and number for the newly selected feature
  feature.setStyle(vectorLayer.getStyle());
  selectedFeature = feature;
  nextNumber++;

  // Refresh the layer to update the styles
  vectorLayer.getSource().refresh();
});
```
In this implementation, we first define a variable to keep track of the currently selected feature (`selectedFeature`) and a variable to keep track of the next number to display (`nextNumber`). We create a new vector layer and add your polygons to its source, and add an event listener for the `click` event on the layer.

Inside the event listener function, we first reset the style of the previously selected feature (if there was one) by calling `setStyle(null)` on it. We then set the style and number for the newly selected feature. We set the style using the `getStyle()` method of the vector layer, which returns the `style` option defined on the layer. We set the `selectedFeature` variable to the newly selected feature and increment the `nextNumber` variable.

We update the style of the features based on their `selectedFeature` property by using an `ol.style.Style` object. We set the default style for the polygons, and if a feature is selected, we update its style to highlight it and display the number label.

Finally, we refresh the layer's source to update the styles.

